			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">another option is to do the following:
 - after reboot and before slaves actually run any tests, make sure that running os.times() on /bin/true will not return an error, and poll for a maximum of 41 seconds until os.times() succeed.

we should ensure that our 32-bit code runs on 32-bit kernels; the differences in address space layout might matter.  perhaps this is more release testing that build testing, but i don't think it hurts much (except some performance) to have a 32-bit kernel on some build slaves.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-12-09T22:16:04.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-12-09T22:16:04.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 2 by b...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=1231#c2" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/1231/comments/full/2" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>